I have 3 microservices with microporfile 2.1 opentracing, Rest Client and Fault tolerance. I redirect all traces to a Jaeger server. The following code works fine

{code:java}
MsBInterface msBResource = RestClientBuilder.newBuilder()
	            .baseUri(URI.create(urlA))
	            .register(new SmallRyeClientTracingFeature(tracer))
	            .build(MsBInterface.class);



RestaurantInterface restaurantResource = RestClientBuilder.newBuilder()
	            .baseUri(URI.create(buidlURL("msA")))
	            .register(new SmallRyeClientTracingFeature(tracer))
	            .build(RestaurantInterface.class);


    @GET
    @Path("/resilience")
    @Produces(MediaType.TEXT_PLAIN) 
    public String resilience() {

        Set<Restaurant> restaurants =  restaurantResource.getAll();    	

	for(Restaurant restaurant : restaurants) {
		msBResource.resilience(restaurant);
	}

        return "OK";
}
{code}

With this expected behavior in Jaeger (check jaeger_working.png attachment)

But when you try to use the Timeout tag in the method

{code:java}
    @GET
    @Fallback(fallbackMethod = "fallback") 
    @Timeout(5000000)
    @Path("/resilience")
    @Produces(MediaType.TEXT_PLAIN)
    public String resilience() {
{code}

It splits the traces (the timeout do no ocurred) (check jaeger_not_working.png attachment)

My pom dependencies

{code:xml}
    <dependency>
      <groupId>org.eclipse.microprofile</groupId>
      <artifactId>microprofile</artifactId>
      <version>2.1</version>
      <type>pom</type>
      <scope>provided</scope>
    </dependency>
    <dependency>
	    <groupId>io.thorntail</groupId>
	    <artifactId>microprofile-opentracing</artifactId>
	</dependency>
	<dependency>
	    <groupId>io.thorntail</groupId>
	    <artifactId>microprofile-fault-tolerance</artifactId>
	</dependency>
	<dependency>
	    <groupId>io.thorntail</groupId>
	    <artifactId>jaeger</artifactId>
	</dependency>
{code}

Say I have a simple JAX-RS resource like this:

{code:java}
@Path("/")
public class RestSimpleResource {
    @Inject
    private MyService myService;

    @GET
    public Response tracedOperation() {
        return Response.ok().entity(myService.hello()).build();
    }
}
{code}

It uses a simple service looking like this:

{code:java}
@ApplicationScoped
public class MyService {
    @Inject
    private Tracer tracer;

    @Traced
    public String hello() {
        tracer.activeSpan().log("Hello tracer");
        return "Hello from traced service";
    }
}
{code}

When MicroProfile OpenTracing is enabled, a single invocation of the JAX-RS endpoint should produce a single trace with two spans: one span for the JAX-RS endpoint itself (because JAX-RS endpoints are traced automatically per MP OpenTracing), and a nested span for the service invocation (because it's {{@Traced}}).

This used to work up to Thorntail 2.2.1.Final, but doesn't work since 2.3.0.Final. The culprit seems to be this change to SmallRye OpenTracing: https://github.com/smallrye/smallrye-opentracing/pull/25 After this change, the interceptor for handling the {{@Traced}} calls no longer comes from SmallRye OpenTracing itself, but from OpenTracing Java Interceptors project. The necessary integration work in Thorntail wasn't done when updating to the new SmallRye OpenTracing version.

When a rest endpoint (JAXRS) try to call a remote endpoint (microprofile-restclient) then it ends with following exception:

{{ERROR [io.undertow.request] (default task-1) UT005023: Exception handling request to /proxy: org.jboss.resteasy.spi.UnhandledException: java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: org/eclipse/microprofile/rest/client/ext/AsyncInvocationInterceptorFa
ctory}}

