When the method fails, I always get the fallback, which is right, and the circuit breaker never opens, which is wrong. It means that the circuit breaker fails to serve its ultimate purpose of not overloading failed external services.

The {{vendor}} scope of MP metrics contains, in the WildFly Swarm implementation, a useless metric called {{test}} (its value seems to correspond to the value of the {{mscLoadedModules}} metric):

{code:javascript}
{
    ...
    "vendor": {
        ...
        "test": {
            "description": "Just testing", 
            "displayName": "test", 
            "tags": "domain=test", 
            "type": "gauge", 
            "unit": "none"
        }
    }
}
{code}

{code:javascript}
{
    ...
    "vendor": {
        ...
        "mscLoadedModules": 252, 
        "test": 252
    }
}
{code}

This metric should be removed, as it's confusing to users.

As part of a Swarm application, I have a simple application metric such as

{code:java}
@ApplicationScoped
public class HelloService {
    @Timed(unit = MetricUnits.MILLISECONDS, name = "hello-time", absolute = true, displayName = "Hello Time", description = "Time of hello invocations")
    public String hello() throws InterruptedException {
        Thread.sleep(new Random().nextInt(100) + 1);
        return "Hello from timed method";
    }
}
{code}

The intent is for the method to take roughly between 1 and 100 millis, and have the duration reported in millis as well.

However, when I run that {{-swarm.jar}} uberjar, trigger the timed method several times and then issue request to {{localhost:8080/metrics}}, I see:

{code:javascript}
{
    "application": {
        "hello-time": {
            ...
            "max": 98169935, 
            "min": 2095416, 
            ...
        }
    }, 
    ...
}
{code}

Clearly the times are in nanoseconds, which is the default for the {{@Timed}} annotation.

Yet the metric metadata say the unit is millis, like specified in the annotation:

{code:javascript}
{
    "application": {
        "hello-time": {
            "description": "Time of hello invocations", 
            "displayName": "Hello Time", 
            "type": "timer", 
            "unit": "milliseconds"
        }
    }, 
    "base": {
        ...
    }
}
{code}

I believe this itself is a blocking issue, though I can't find a single place in the MP Metrics spec that would conclusively confirm or refute.

I have another argument, though, that makes it clear that there's definitely something wrong: if I request the metrics in the Prometheus format, I see:

{code}
...
application:hello_time_min_seconds 2095.416
application:hello_time_max_seconds 98169.935
...
{code}

This is very clearly wrong -- the invocations don't take thousands of seconds!

I believe that, when converting the values to seconds as MP Metrics spec requires, WildFly Swarm acted as if the metric was in millis (per the metadata!). Problem is that the values are actually in nanos!

To conclude, I think these 2 wrong outputs are actually caused by a single problem.

As part of a Swarm application, I have a simple application metric such as

{code:java}
@ApplicationScoped
public class HelloService {
    @Counted(monotonic = true, name = "hello", absolute = true, displayName = "HELLO", description = "Number of hello invocations")
    public String hello() {
        return "Hello from counted method";
    }
}
{code}

When I run that {{-swarm.jar}} uberjar, trigger the metered method (this is so that the metric is registered, see SWARM-1897) and then issue an {{OPTIONS}} request to {{localhost:8080/metrics}}, I don't see the {{displayName}} and {{description}}:

{code:javascript}
{
    "application": {
        "hello": {
            "displayName": "hello", 
            "type": "counter", 
            "unit": "none"
        }
    }, 
    "base": {
        ...
    }
}
{code}

As part of a Swarm application, I have a simple application metric such as

{code:java}
@ApplicationScoped
public class HelloService {
    @Counted(monotonic = true, name = "hello", absolute = true, displayName = "HELLO", description = "Number of hello invocations")
    public String hello() {
        return "Hello from counted method";
    }
}
{code}

When I run that {{-swarm.jar}} uberjar, the metric isn't registered immediately, which I can confirm by issuing an {{OPTIONS}} request to {{localhost:8080/metrics}}.

Only when I trigger the metered method is the metric registered.

Per my understanding of the MP Metrics specification, this is wrong.

Specifically:

Section 5.1 says:

{quote}
The implementation must scan the application at deploy time for Annotations and register the Metrics along with their metadata in the application MetricsRegistry.
{quote}

This is pretty clear -- it should happen at deploy time.

There's also a small supporting evidence in section 2.1.3:

{quote}
Metadata must not change over the lifetime of a process (i.e. it is not allowed to return the units as seconds in one retrieval and as hours in a subsequent one). The reason behind it is that e.g. a monitoring agent on Kubernetes may read the metadata once it sees the new container and store it. It may not periodically re-query the process for the metadata.
{quote}

This is mainly concerned with metadata of a single metric, but it also makes a very good argument for why the _set_ of _all_ metrics shouldn't change during the application lifetime. I.e., metrics should be registered eagerly.

