*What*
It is possible to get past the login screen of the mobile app and access other views in the app, despite the user profile data in localstorage being encrypted. An attacker can use a fake session key and get the SHA256 of the key, and then encrypt some profile data object using AES (with the SHA256 of the session key) to generate ciphertext that won't crash the application, and will allow unauthorized access.

_Steps to Reproduce_
Open up the Mobile App in a browser and run the following in the console.

{code:java} 
localStorage.setItem("fh.wfm.profileData", "");
localStorage.setItem("fh_session_token._index_", '["fh_session_token.sessionToken"]'); 
localStorage.setItem("fh_session_token.sessionToken", '{"sessionToken":"123"}'); 
{code} 

Change the url to point from `/login` to any of the following, you might need to hit enter twice in the address bar in your browser. 
* /settings. 
* /files - form here upload a file, check the portal app for the file to see that it got uploaded. 

*How*
We should check that the session token is valid on all routes in the mobile application before proceeding to render that view. 

The verify session endpoint already exists in the user module, we will need to use this function to check if the session token is valid.

The Topics utilities in the mediator don't allow for async operations followed by a custom publishing of the result since it expects a promise to be returned and to supply the result of the operation so it can be published to the conventional 'done:' prefixed topic.

Currently when no value is returned from a handler the 'done:' topic is still published to but with undefined as a value.

Examples:


{code:java}
topics.prefix('wfm').entity('user')
// this works
.on('list', function() {
  // The following should return a Promise
  // result gets published to done:wfm:user:list
  return getAllAsync(this.entity);
})
// this doesn't
.on('delete', function(id) {
  // note this Promise isn't returned since we want to publish to somewhere else
  deleteAsync(this.identity, id).then(function() {
    topics.mediator.publish('some:other:topic', id);
  })
})
{code}

*What*
The full user profile data is being returned in the receiver object for a message in the mobile client and portal app. This is also being stored in *plaintext* on the mobile device.

Eg. in records.dataset_messages, 

