30/Aug/18 2:31 PM;ssilvert;Here is some TypeScript code that works for this.  Keycloak is very particular about how you create the hash.  Make sure you encode using UTF-8 and that you follow the base64url specification.
{code}
    private generateUri(providerId: string, clientId: string): string {
        let uri: string = 'http://localhost:8080/auth/realms/master/broker/' + providerId + '/link';
        const nonce: string = createRandomString(); // however you want to do this
        const sessionState: string = KeycloakInstance.tokenParsed.session_state;
        const input: string = nonce + sessionState + clientId + providerId;
        const check: string = crypto.SHA256(crypto.enc.Utf8.parse(input));
        const hash: string = this.base64url(check);  // see note below*

        uri += '?nonce=' + nonce;
        uri += '&hash=' + hash;
        uri += '&client_id=account';
        uri += '&redirect_uri=' + this.redirectUri;

        return uri;
    }

    private base64url(source: string): string {
        // Encode in classical base64
        let encodedSource = crypto.enc.Base64.stringify(source);

        // Remove padding equal characters
        encodedSource = encodedSource.replace(/=+$/, '');

        // Replace characters according to base64url specifications
        encodedSource = encodedSource.replace(/\+/g, '-');
        encodedSource = encodedSource.replace(/\//g, '_');

        return encodedSource;
    }
{code}

*This base64Url() method is found posted on several blogs.  I don't know who the original author is.  You might want to use a javascript package like "base64url" or "base64-url" instead.

